Fantastic condition Savage model 1917 in .32 auto. One of the first "high capacity" pistols, it was marketed as a home defense pistol sporting a 10-round double stack magazine. Produced between 1917 and 1923, this pistol exemplifies the roaring 20's with it's beautiful Art Deco design. Hollywood perfectly cast this as the weapon of choice used by Jude Laws assassin character in the film "Road To Perdition". These came in a matte blues finish, this one being in 95% condition with the only thinning on some high spots as to be expected of a gun this age.

The pistol functions flawlessly with quality .32 ammo which is once again abundantly available and affordable. High velocity european ammo will ensure reliable cycling (brands like Fiocchi, Geco, and PPU which are all available). Comes with one 10-round magazine and a Makarov flap holster which fits it perfectly.

If you price this gun in this condition on Gunbroker, Gunsamerica, etc. you will see that I have priced to sell. You won't find one in this condition any cheaper. My price of $325 is firm. No trades, cash only and I will need to see a valid Indiana drivers license and CC license. I will not ship, FTF only.

Fantastic collectible gun for those interested in quality American made firearms of the early 20th century, firearms featured in films, or Art Deco pieces from the 1920's. And yes, it is also a fun range gun and with "Ten Rounds Fast" (as the original ads say), it is a viable self-defense weapon.

title: For Sale:  1 lb. each - IMR 4007 SSC & Hodgdon H335
postcontent:
Unopened canisters of smokeless powder.

I have found IMR 4007 SSC to be the most accurate powder for my .223 Remington loads out to 200 yards.  However, the minimum bullet weight is 75 grains.  I am running an HKMR556 with a 1-7 twist.  Using 77 grain SMK, I have emptied a 30-round magazine with all shots being 1" at 200 yards (caveat: day was virtually windless).  The muzzle velocity is definitely not the fastest, but the chamber pressure is freakishly low and recoil is such that ACCURATE rapid fire comes effortlessly.  I really like this powder, I have several pounds more in my stash.  

As for the H335, I do not know much about this powder; I have never used it.  All I know is what I've read:  Medium to high muzzle velocities for a broad range of calibers. I bought this pound about a year ago out of desperation (during the 2013 shortage) but was fortunate enough to find my 'go-to' powders shortly thereafter.

$25 each or $45 for both.  Not trying to turn a profit, just want to recoup my money.  Cash and carry.

title: For Sale:  Valtro PM-5
postcontent:
The Valtro PM-5 shotgun had been developed by the Italian company Valtro back inthe 1980s and is still in production. It is used by various law enforcement and military forces, including the French Navy. The PM-5 is almost unique in that it has a detachable box magazine, while most pump action shotguns are built using underbarrel tube magazines. The detachable box magazine greatly improves reloading time and balance. The only drawback is the increased height of the loaded weapon, but it is not a major issue in most cases.
They are reportedly actually manufactured by Benelli. Import has been banned for several years now but are used in Europe by numerous Security forces.
Renowned for their simplicity, lightweight and reliability, this pump action 12 ga. shotgun has sold on the US market for as much as $1200.00.
